# Command /sync-library-rules

When the user types **`/sync-library-rules`**, automatically scan all projects under `C:\opt\src` and import missing rules from `@Library` based on project pattern/technology matches.

## Goal

- Find projects that already use Cursor rules/commands (`*.mdc` under `.cursor/`)
- Detect which Library rule themes fit each project
- Copy only missing matching rules into `.cursor/rules/`
- Copy matching command files into `.cursor/commands/` when applicable
- Materialize skills into `.cursor/skills/<name>/SKILL.md`

## Step 1 — Discover Target Projects

Use PowerShell 7:

```powershell
$sourceRoot = "C:\opt\src"
$projects = Get-ChildItem -Path $sourceRoot -Directory -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue

$targets = foreach ($p in $projects) {
    $cursorDir = Join-Path $p.FullName ".cursor"
    if (-not (Test-Path $cursorDir)) { continue }

    $mdc = Get-ChildItem -Path $cursorDir -Recurse -Filter "*.mdc" -File -ErrorAction SilentlyContinue
    if ($mdc.Count -gt 0) { $p }
}
```

## Step 2 — Detect Matching Library Themes Per Project

For each target project, detect themes using these signals:

| Signal | Theme |
|--------|-------|
| `*.csproj` exists | `CSharp-WinApp` (default C#) |
| `.csproj` contains `Microsoft.AspNetCore` | `CSharp-WebApp` |
| `.csproj` contains `<UseWPF>true` | `WPF` |
| `.csproj` contains `IBM.Data.Db2` / `Net.IBM.Data.Db2` | `Db2` |
| `.csproj` contains `NLog` or `Serilog` | `Logging` |
| `.csproj` contains `DedgeAuth` refs | `DedgeAuth` |
| `*.ps1` exists | `PowerShell` |
| `*.wxs` or `*.wixproj` exists | `Installer` |
| `*.html`/`*.css`/`*.js` exists | `Web-UI` |
| UNC paths (`\\server\`) in source files | `Server` |
| test projects/files exist | `Testing` |

Always include these baseline themes:

- `Agent`
- `Git`
- `Documentation`
- `Security`

## Step 3 — Build Candidate Rule List

For each detected theme, collect files from:

- `C:\opt\src\CursorRulesLibrary\Library\<Theme>\*.mdc`

For commands, use:

- `C:\opt\src\CursorRulesLibrary\Library\Commands\*.mdc`

## Step 4 — Compare and Import Missing Files

For each project:

1. Ensure folders exist:
   - `.cursor/rules`
   - `.cursor/commands`
   - `.cursor/skills`
2. Compare by filename:
   - If missing in project -> copy from Library
   - If exists and different content -> keep existing and report `DIFFERS` (manual review)
   - If exists and same content -> skip
3. Never place command files in `.cursor/rules`
4. Convert `Library/Skills/*.mdc` to `.cursor/skills/<skill-name>/SKILL.md`

## Step 5 — Execute Pattern-Based Import

Use this flow (do not do blind copy of all themes):

```powershell
$libraryRoot = "C:\opt\src\CursorRulesLibrary\Library"

foreach ($project in $targets) {
    $projectRoot = $project.FullName
    $ruleDir = Join-Path $projectRoot ".cursor\rules"
    $commandDir = Join-Path $projectRoot ".cursor\commands"
    New-Item -ItemType Directory -Path $ruleDir -Force | Out-Null
    New-Item -ItemType Directory -Path $commandDir -Force | Out-Null

    # 1) Detect themes from signals in projectRoot
    # 2) Add baseline themes: Agent, Git, Documentation, Security
    # 3) Copy only missing files from matching Library\<Theme>\*.mdc to $ruleDir
    # 4) For commands, copy only missing Library\Commands\command-*.mdc to $commandDir
    # 5) If file exists and hash differs, mark DIFFERS and do not overwrite
}
```

## Step 6 — Report Results

Present a compact table per project:

| Project | Added Rules | Added Commands | Differing Existing | Notes |
|---------|-------------|----------------|--------------------|-------|

Then list any projects needing manual merge due to `DIFFERS`.

## Step 7 — Git Actions

If files changed, run:

```powershell
git add .
git commit -m "chore(rules): sync matching Library rules and commands"
git push
```

If some repos fail to push (missing upstream/remote), report those repos explicitly.

